-- Pair 1: Smooth & Restore (botox_cosmetic__juvederm_vollure_xc)
-- Review status: PENDING
-- Tier: combination | Evidence: strong
UPDATE agent_fuel_documents
SET
    content = '{"fuel_type":"combination","template_version":"1.0","pair_key":"botox_cosmetic__juvederm_vollure_xc","patient_facing_name":"Smooth & Restore","one_line_positioning":"Botox relaxes the muscles that cause expression lines while Vollure restores the mid-depth volume that muscle relaxation alone cannot address.","package_goal":"Reduce expression lines and soften nasolabial folds","ideal_candidate":"Adult patients presenting with both dynamic upper-face wrinkles (forehead, crow''s feet, glabellar lines) and moderate-to-severe static mid-face lines or nasolabial folds that persist at rest.","not_ideal_candidate":"Patients with active skin infection at injection sites, known hypersensitivity to botulinum toxin or HA components, or patients seeking exclusively volume restoration without concern for dynamic lines.","concern_tags":["Fine Lines","Volume Loss","Dynamic Wrinkles","Nasolabial Folds","Skin Aging"],"why_together":"Botox addresses movement-caused lines through neuromodulation; Vollure fills the static mid-depth volume loss that muscle relaxation cannot restore. These two mechanisms operate at different tissue layers and address different root causes of facial aging.","A_solves":"Botox relaxes the muscles that create dynamic expression lines (forehead, crow''s feet, glabellar lines) — the lines that appear when you move your face.","A_does_not_solve":"Botox cannot restore lost volume or soften lines that remain at rest when the face is relaxed.","B_adds":"Vollure restores mid-depth volume in the nasolabial folds and moderate facial lines that persist even when the face is at rest — the kind of lines neurotoxin cannot treat.","clinical_rationale":"Neurotoxin relaxes dynamic muscles; Vollure restores mid-depth volume (nasolabial folds). Published evidence supports the combination of BoNT-A with HA fillers as superior to either modality alone (DOI 10.1097/DSS.0000000000000754). Botox addresses movement-based lines that Vollure cannot treat, while Vollure addresses static volume loss that Botox cannot restore. Together they provide a more complete facial rejuvenation than either treatment alone.","patient_education_summary":"Botox helps relax the muscles that cause expression lines — like frown lines and crow''s feet. But it can''t address the deeper lines that stay even when your face is at rest — like the lines that run from your nose to the corners of your mouth, or the moderate lines around your mouth area. Those are caused by volume loss, not muscle movement. Vollure is designed specifically for those nasolabial folds and moderate facial lines, softening them by restoring volume at the right depth. Many patients find that treating both the movement-based lines and these static lines creates a more complete, natural-looking result.","staff_close":"When a patient comes in concerned about looking tired or aged, explain: ''Botox can help with the lines around your eyes and forehead — those are caused by muscle movement. But if you''re also noticing deeper lines from your nose to the corners of your mouth — those nasolabial folds — those are caused by volume loss, which Botox can''t address. Vollure is designed to soften those specific lines by restoring volume at the mid-depth level.''","staff_talking_points":"Some patients choose to address both in the same visit, while others prefer to start with one and see how they feel. The key is helping patients understand these are two different types of lines — one from movement, one from volume loss — not an upsell. If timing is a concern, neurotoxin can be done first; filler can follow 2 weeks later once the muscle response is visible, which helps determine exactly where volume restoration is most needed.","do_not_say":{"universal":["Unsupported clinical claims (e.g., ''clinically proven to reverse aging'')","Guarantees (e.g., ''I guarantee you''ll love the results'')","''You need this'' pressure (e.g., ''You really need both'')","Fear-based selling (e.g., ''Without this, your skin will only get worse'')","Competitor disparagement","''Liquid facelift'' overclaims","''No downtime'' when downtime exists","Permanent result claims","Off-label combination approval claims","''No risk'' statements","Price/value claims practices may not honor","Before/after exaggerations (e.g., ''20 years younger'')"],"pair_specific":["Do not call this a ''liquid facelift'' or ''non-surgical facelift'' — these terms overclaim the outcome and create unrealistic expectations.","Do not imply that Vollure will ''plump'' or ''inflate'' the face — describe it as restoring mid-depth volume or softening static lines.","Do not state the combination is ''FDA approved'' as a combination — each product has its own FDA indication; the combination is used in clinical practice, not as a co-approved package.","Do not guarantee how long results will last — durations vary by patient metabolism, anatomy, and lifestyle."],"practice_specific":[]},"top_objections":[{"objection_type":"cost","patient_says":"That sounds expensive. Do I need to do both at once?","handling_language":"You absolutely don''t have to do both at once. Many patients start with one treatment and add the other later. Starting with Botox lets you see how the dynamic lines respond first, and if you''d like to address the static lines around your mouth or nose at a future visit, that option is there. There''s no pressure to do everything at once.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say ''it''s worth it'' or imply they are missing out if they don''t do both. Don''t suggest a payment plan unless they ask."},{"objection_type":"do_I_need_both","patient_says":"Can''t Botox just handle all of my concerns?","handling_language":"Botox is excellent for lines caused by muscle movement — around your eyes, forehead, and between your brows. But it can''t address lines that are still visible when your face is completely relaxed, like the fold from your nose to the corner of your mouth. Those are caused by volume loss, which requires a different approach. Whether you want to address that is entirely your choice.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say ''Botox won''t work'' — it will work for what it''s designed for. Don''t say ''you need filler too'' — frame it as a different problem, not a deficiency."},{"objection_type":"fear_of_looking_overdone","patient_says":"I don''t want to look puffy or fake.","handling_language":"That''s a completely valid concern. Good filler placement should restore what was naturally there before — not add anything that looks unnatural. Vollure is designed for moderate facial lines, not dramatic volume addition. The goal is a subtle, natural result, and your provider controls the amount placed.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t dismiss the concern. Don''t say ''you won''t be able to tell.'' Don''t say ''everyone does this now.''"},{"objection_type":"downtime","patient_says":"How long will I need to recover? I have plans this weekend.","handling_language":"Most patients can resume normal activities the same day. With any injection, there''s a chance of temporary redness, minor swelling, or bruising at the treatment sites — this varies by person. Some patients prefer to schedule a few days before an important event just in case, while others go right back to work. Your provider can walk you through what to expect based on your skin and your plans.","do_not_say_in_response":"Do not say ''no downtime'' — there is potential for temporary bruising or swelling. Don''t minimize legitimate side effect concerns."},{"objection_type":"I_will_think_about_it","patient_says":"Let me think about it and maybe come back for the filler another time.","handling_language":"Of course — this is your decision and there''s no rush. If you''d like, we can note in your chart what we discussed so it''s easy to revisit at your next visit. Many patients start with Botox and then decide to add filler once they''ve seen how the dynamic lines respond. That''s a completely reasonable approach.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t create urgency about pricing or timing. Don''t say ''the sooner the better'' in a way that feels pressured."}],"sequencing_note":"Neurotoxin administered first in same-session protocols. If sequential: neurotoxin 2 weeks before filler allows muscle response to be assessed before filling static lines.","timing_note":"Same session or sequential visits. If sequential: 2-week interval between neurotoxin and filler.","downtime_note":"Minimal. Temporary redness, minor swelling, or bruising possible at injection sites for either or both treatments. Botox: full effect visible at 7-14 days. Vollure: immediate volume with minor swelling resolving over days. Post-cannula 48-hour makeup restriction may apply to filler component.","same_session_ok":true,"maintenance_story":"Botox every 3-4 months; Juvederm Vollure XC every 12-18 months. Patients typically schedule neurotoxin visits more frequently, with filler touchups planned at natural renewal intervals. Many patients align one annual filler visit with the start of a new neurotoxin cycle.","rebooking_trigger":"At your 2-week follow-up for Botox, we can assess how the dynamic lines have responded and discuss whether you''d like to address the nasolabial folds at that point or at your next scheduled visit.","next_visit_prompt":"At your Botox follow-up or next visit, we''ll assess the dynamic line response. If volume restoration is a goal, that conversation can happen when you''re ready.","source_support_summary":"PubMed DOI 10.1097/DSS.0000000000000754: BoNT-A and fillers may be performed together in either sequence; combination is superior to either alone. FDA label — Botox Cosmetic: indicated for glabellar lines, lateral canthal lines, and forehead lines in adults. FDA label — Juvederm Vollure XC: indicated for correction of moderate to severe facial wrinkles and folds including nasolabial folds in adults over 21. Expert consensus: neurotoxin-first sequencing in same-session protocols is accepted clinical practice.","evidence_level":"strong","review_status":"draft","audience":["agent","staff"],"patient_safe":false,"last_reviewed":null,"reviewed_by":null}'::jsonb,
    status  = 'draft'
WHERE fuel_type = 'pairing_fuel'
  AND content->>'pair_key' = 'botox_cosmetic__juvederm_vollure_xc';

-- Pair 2: Smooth & Lift (botox_cosmetic__juvederm_voluma_xc)
-- Review status: PENDING
-- Tier: combination | Evidence: strong
UPDATE agent_fuel_documents
SET
    content = '{"fuel_type":"combination","template_version":"1.0","pair_key":"botox_cosmetic__juvederm_voluma_xc","patient_facing_name":"Smooth & Lift","one_line_positioning":"Botox relaxes expression lines while Voluma restores the deep cheek structure that supports and lifts the face.","package_goal":"Reduce dynamic wrinkles and restore midface volume and contour","ideal_candidate":"Adult patients presenting with both dynamic upper-face wrinkles and age-related volume loss in the midface or cheek area creating a hollow, flattened, or descended appearance.","not_ideal_candidate":"Patients seeking only surface line reduction without interest in midface structure, or patients with hypersensitivity to botulinum toxin or HA components.","concern_tags":["Dynamic Wrinkles","Cheek Volume Loss","Midface Aging","Volume Loss","Facial Contour"],"why_together":"Botox addresses movement-caused lines through neuromodulation; Voluma restores deep structural volume in the cheek area through HA gel scaffold. They work at completely different tissue layers — Botox at the neuromuscular level, Voluma at the deep supraperiosteal/subcutaneous level.","A_solves":"Botox relaxes the muscles that create dynamic expression lines (crow''s feet, frown lines, forehead) — lines caused by repetitive muscle movement.","A_does_not_solve":"Botox cannot restore the structural volume lost in the cheeks or midface over time due to bone, fat pad, and collagen changes.","B_adds":"Voluma restores deep cheek volume and contour in the midface where bone and fat pad loss creates a hollow, aged appearance that neurotoxin cannot address.","clinical_rationale":"Neurotoxin relaxes dynamic muscles; Voluma restores deep cheek volume. Botox addresses movement-based lines (crow''s feet, frown lines, forehead) while Voluma provides structural volume restoration in the midface where bone and fat pad loss creates a hollow, aged appearance. Published evidence supports combination use of BoNT-A with HA fillers, with data suggesting enhanced outcomes compared to either modality alone (DOI 10.1097/DSS.0000000000000754). Together they address both the upper face (dynamic lines) and midface (volume loss) for more balanced facial rejuvenation.","patient_education_summary":"Botox helps relax the muscles that cause expression lines — like frown lines and crow''s feet. But it can''t restore the deep volume that''s been lost over time in areas like the cheeks. If you''re noticing that your cheeks look flatter or more hollow than they used to, that''s a different kind of aging — it''s structural volume loss from bone and fat pad changes. Voluma is designed specifically to restore that deep cheek structure, giving back the lift and contour that supports the rest of your face. Many patients find that treating both the movement-based lines and the midface volume creates a more balanced, natural-looking result.","staff_close":"Botox can help with the lines around your eyes and forehead — those are caused by muscle movement. But if you''re also noticing that your cheeks look flatter or more hollow than they used to, that''s structural volume loss in the midface, which Botox can''t address. Voluma is designed for deep cheek restoration — it provides the structural support that lifts and contours your midface.","staff_talking_points":"Some patients choose to address both in the same visit, while others prefer to start with one and see how they feel. The key is helping patients understand these are two different problems at two different depths — not an upsell. Neuromodulation preserves filler longevity by reducing mechanical stress on treated areas, so the combination can extend the practical life of Voluma results.","do_not_say":{"universal":["Unsupported clinical claims (e.g., ''clinically proven to reverse aging'')","Guarantees (e.g., ''I guarantee you''ll love the results'')","''You need this'' pressure (e.g., ''You really need both'')","Fear-based selling (e.g., ''Without this, your skin will only get worse'')","Competitor disparagement","''Liquid facelift'' overclaims","''No downtime'' when downtime exists","Permanent result claims","Off-label combination approval claims","''No risk'' statements","Price/value claims practices may not honor","Before/after exaggerations (e.g., ''20 years younger'')"],"pair_specific":["Do not describe Voluma as ''lifting'' the cheeks in a way that implies a surgical lift — describe it as restoring structural support and volume.","Do not call this a ''liquid facelift'' or ''non-surgical facelift'' — these terms overclaim and create unrealistic expectations.","Do not imply that the combination is ''FDA approved'' as a package — each product has its own FDA indication.","Do not guarantee cheek volume restoration duration — Voluma results vary by patient and metabolism."],"practice_specific":[]},"top_objections":[{"objection_type":"cost","patient_says":"Both at once seems like a lot. Can I just do Botox for now?","handling_language":"Absolutely — many patients start with Botox to address the expression lines and decide later whether they want to add volume restoration. They''re addressing two different things, so you can do them in either order or in separate visits.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t imply they''re missing something by not doing both. Don''t use urgency about pricing."},{"objection_type":"do_I_need_both","patient_says":"Will Botox make my cheeks look lifted?","handling_language":"Botox relaxes muscles, so it can soften the lines around your eyes and forehead — that can make you look more rested. But the cheek area specifically involves structural volume, not muscle movement. If the hollowness or flatness in your cheeks is a concern, that''s a different issue that Voluma addresses. Botox wouldn''t change the cheek contour itself.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t dismiss what Botox can achieve. Be accurate that Botox doesn''t add volume."},{"objection_type":"fear_of_looking_overdone","patient_says":"I don''t want to look like I have ''pillow face.''","handling_language":"That concern makes complete sense, and it''s why Voluma is designed specifically for deep cheek structure, not surface filling. The goal is to restore what was there naturally — appropriate volume at the right depth — not to add anything that looks artificial. The amount placed is carefully controlled, and the result should look like you, not like something was added.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t dismiss the concern. Don''t say ''nobody will know.'' Don''t say ''the old look is out.''"},{"objection_type":"downtime","patient_says":"I have an event next week. Is it safe to do both now?","handling_language":"Good to know. With filler, there''s some chance of minor swelling or bruising that can take a few days to fully settle. If your event is important, you may want to consider doing the Botox today and scheduling Voluma for a few weeks after the event. Your provider can help you plan the timing.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say ''no downtime'' — filler can cause swelling and bruising. Don''t dismiss the practical concern."},{"objection_type":"I_will_think_about_it","patient_says":"I''m not sure about the filler part. Can I come back for that?","handling_language":"Of course. Voluma is an independent decision from Botox — you can do the neurotoxin today and revisit the cheek volume conversation at any time. We can note what we discussed and revisit it at your next appointment.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t create urgency. Don''t say ''prices may go up.''"}],"sequencing_note":"Neurotoxin administered first in same-session protocols. If sequential: neurotoxin 2 weeks before filler allows muscle response to be assessed before placing deep volume.","timing_note":"Same session or sequential visits. If sequential: neurotoxin 2 weeks before Voluma.","downtime_note":"Minimal. Temporary redness, minor swelling, or bruising possible at injection sites. Botox: full effect at 7-14 days. Voluma: immediate volume with potential swelling resolving over 1-2 weeks at deep injection sites.","same_session_ok":true,"maintenance_story":"Botox every 3-4 months; Juvederm Voluma XC every 18-24 months. The less-frequent Voluma maintenance schedule means patients can align filler touchups with less disruption to their regular Botox schedule. Neuromodulation may preserve Voluma longevity by reducing mechanical stress.","rebooking_trigger":"At your Botox follow-up, we can check how the dynamic lines have responded and discuss whether you''d like to address the cheek structure at that visit or schedule it separately.","next_visit_prompt":"If midface volume is a concern, we can discuss Voluma at your next visit. The Botox follow-up at 2 weeks is a natural time to have that conversation.","source_support_summary":"PubMed DOI 10.1097/DSS.0000000000000754: BoNT-A and fillers may be performed together in either sequence; combination is superior to either alone. FDA label — Botox Cosmetic: indicated for glabellar lines, lateral canthal lines, and forehead lines in adults. FDA label — Juvederm Voluma XC: indicated for correction of age-related volume deficit in the cheek area in adults over 21. Expert consensus: neurotoxin-first sequencing in same-session protocols is accepted clinical practice; neuromodulation may preserve filler longevity by reducing mechanical stress.","evidence_level":"strong","review_status":"draft","audience":["agent","staff"],"patient_safe":false,"last_reviewed":null,"reviewed_by":null}'::jsonb,
    status  = 'draft'
WHERE fuel_type = 'pairing_fuel'
  AND content->>'pair_key' = 'botox_cosmetic__juvederm_voluma_xc';

-- Pair 3: Smooth & Restore (Restylane) (botox_cosmetic__restylane_lyft)
-- Review status: PENDING
-- Tier: combination | Evidence: moderate
UPDATE agent_fuel_documents
SET
    content = '{"fuel_type":"combination","template_version":"1.0","pair_key":"botox_cosmetic__restylane_lyft","patient_facing_name":"Smooth & Restore (Restylane)","one_line_positioning":"Botox relaxes expression lines while Restylane Lyft restores structural midface volume or hand volume through a complementary mechanism.","package_goal":"Reduce dynamic wrinkles and restore midface or hand volume","ideal_candidate":"Adult patients presenting with both dynamic upper-face wrinkles and midface volume loss or dorsal hand volume loss seeking a cross-brand combination of Allergan neurotoxin with Galderma filler.","not_ideal_candidate":"Patients hypersensitive to gram-positive bacterial proteins (Restylane) or botulinum toxin. Patients seeking only one treatment modality.","concern_tags":["Dynamic Wrinkles","Midface Volume Loss","Hand Volume Loss","Skin Aging"],"why_together":"Botox addresses movement-caused lines; Restylane Lyft restores structural midface or hand volume. The complementarity is mechanism-based — neuromodulation vs HA gel scaffold — not brand-specific.","A_solves":"Botox relaxes the muscles causing expression lines (crow''s feet, frown lines, forehead) — the wrinkles that appear with facial movement.","A_does_not_solve":"Botox cannot restore lost volume in the midface or dorsal hands.","B_adds":"Restylane Lyft restores structural volume in the midface and has a unique dual FDA indication for both midface and dorsal hand augmentation — volume territory Botox cannot address.","clinical_rationale":"Neurotoxin relaxes dynamic muscles; Lyft restores midface or hand volume. Cross-brand combination (Allergan Botox + Galderma Restylane) demonstrates that the complementarity is mechanism-based, not brand-specific. Botox handles movement-based lines while Lyft provides structural volume restoration in the midface and hands, addressing two fundamentally different aspects of aging. Category-level evidence supports BoNT-A + HA filler combinations (DOI 10.1097/DSS.0000000000000754); no product-specific study exists for this cross-brand pair. Evidence is extrapolated from category.","patient_education_summary":"Botox helps relax the muscles that cause expression lines — like frown lines and crow''s feet. But it can''t restore volume that''s been lost over time. If you''re noticing both lines from movement AND a loss of fullness in your cheeks or around your mouth, filler addresses that volume loss through a completely different approach. Many patients find that treating both concerns creates a more balanced, natural-looking result than treating either one alone.","staff_close":"Botox can help with the lines around your eyes and forehead — those are caused by muscle movement. If you''re also noticing that your cheeks look flatter than they used to, that''s volume loss, which Botox can''t address. Restylane Lyft works on a different layer to restore that structure.","staff_talking_points":"Some patients choose to address both in the same visit, while others prefer to start with one and see how they feel. Note that Restylane Lyft also has a unique FDA indication for dorsal hand volume — relevant if a patient mentions hand aging in addition to facial concerns. The cross-brand nature (Allergan + Galderma) is clinically irrelevant but may come up in loyalty program conversations.","do_not_say":{"universal":["Unsupported clinical claims (e.g., ''clinically proven to reverse aging'')","Guarantees (e.g., ''I guarantee you''ll love the results'')","''You need this'' pressure (e.g., ''You really need both'')","Fear-based selling (e.g., ''Without this, your skin will only get worse'')","Competitor disparagement","''Liquid facelift'' overclaims","''No downtime'' when downtime exists","Permanent result claims","Off-label combination approval claims","''No risk'' statements","Price/value claims practices may not honor","Before/after exaggerations (e.g., ''20 years younger'')"],"pair_specific":["Do not state that the combination is FDA approved as a combination — each product has its own individual FDA indication.","Do not dismiss the cross-brand nature as a negative or positive — it is simply clinically irrelevant to the mechanism.","Do not overpromise on evidence strength — there is no product-specific published study for Botox + Restylane Lyft; the rationale is category-level.","Do not claim Restylane Lyft provides the same depth of midface restoration as products designed for deeper planes — describe it as midface volume restoration accurately."],"practice_specific":[]},"top_objections":[{"objection_type":"cost","patient_says":"I wasn''t planning on filler today — can I just do Botox?","handling_language":"Of course. Botox and filler address different things, so they don''t have to happen at the same time. You can start with Botox today and revisit the volume conversation whenever you''re ready.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t suggest the opportunity will pass. Don''t mention pricing pressure."},{"objection_type":"do_I_need_both","patient_says":"Will Botox take care of the fullness issue too?","handling_language":"Botox relaxes the muscles that create expression lines — it''s great for that. But the fullness or flatness you may be noticing in your cheeks is from volume changes in the tissue, not from muscle activity. Botox can''t add volume. That''s what filler is designed for — a completely different mechanism.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t be dismissive of what Botox achieves. Just clarify the mechanism difference clearly."},{"objection_type":"cross_brand_concern","patient_says":"I thought Allergan and Galderma products don''t go together?","handling_language":"There''s actually no issue with combining products from different manufacturers — they work through completely different mechanisms in different tissue layers, so there''s no interaction between them. The choice of which filler to use is based on what fits your anatomy and goals, not which brand it comes from.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t disparage either manufacturer. Don''t imply one brand is better."},{"objection_type":"downtime","patient_says":"I''m worried about bruising if I do both at once.","handling_language":"That''s a reasonable concern. With any injection, there''s some chance of temporary bruising, and doing both treatments in one visit does involve more injection sites. Some patients prefer to space them out for exactly that reason. If you have something coming up where you want to minimize the chance of visible bruising, we can schedule them a couple of weeks apart.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say ''no bruising'' — bruising is possible. Don''t dismiss the practical concern."},{"objection_type":"I_will_think_about_it","patient_says":"I''ll think about adding the filler — can we just do Botox today?","handling_language":"Absolutely. We''ll do the Botox today, and if you decide later you''d like to discuss the filler, we can pick up that conversation at any time.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t create urgency. Don''t follow up with a hard close."}],"sequencing_note":"Neurotoxin administered first in same-session protocols. If sequential: neurotoxin 2 weeks before filler.","timing_note":"Same session or sequential visits. If sequential: 2-week interval recommended.","downtime_note":"Minimal. Temporary redness, minor swelling, or bruising at injection sites for either or both treatments. Botox: full effect at 7-14 days. Restylane Lyft: immediate volume with potential minor swelling. Post-treatment restriction per provider protocol.","same_session_ok":true,"maintenance_story":"Botox every 3-4 months; Restylane Lyft every 12-18 months (product-dependent, individual variation). Patients typically schedule neurotoxin more frequently, with filler aligned to natural renewal cycles.","rebooking_trigger":"At your Botox follow-up, we can revisit the volume conversation. Restylane Lyft also has an FDA indication for hand rejuvenation if that becomes a concern at any point.","next_visit_prompt":"If you''d like to discuss midface volume or hand volume at your next visit, we can assess together.","source_support_summary":"PubMed DOI 10.1097/DSS.0000000000000754: BoNT-A and HA fillers may be performed together in either sequence; combination is superior to either alone. Category-level evidence — extrapolated to this cross-brand pair. FDA label — Botox Cosmetic: indicated for glabellar lines, lateral canthal lines, and forehead lines in adults. FDA label — Restylane Lyft: indicated for midface volume deficit and dorsal hand volume loss in adults over 21 (dual facial + hand indication). Accepted clinical practice: cross-brand neurotoxin + filler combinations are commonly used; complementarity is mechanism-based.","evidence_level":"moderate","review_status":"draft","audience":["agent","staff"],"patient_safe":false,"last_reviewed":null,"reviewed_by":null}'::jsonb,
    status  = 'draft'
WHERE fuel_type = 'pairing_fuel'
  AND content->>'pair_key' = 'botox_cosmetic__restylane_lyft';

-- Pair 4: Smooth & Soften (Perioral) (botox_cosmetic__rha_redensity)
-- Review status: PENDING
-- Tier: combination | Evidence: moderate
UPDATE agent_fuel_documents
SET
    content = '{"fuel_type":"combination","template_version":"1.0","pair_key":"botox_cosmetic__rha_redensity","patient_facing_name":"Smooth & Soften (Perioral)","one_line_positioning":"Botox reduces upper-face expression lines while RHA Redensity softens the perioral fine lines that neurotoxin cannot address.","package_goal":"Reduce expression lines across upper and lower face with zone-specific treatments","ideal_candidate":"Adult patients presenting with upper-face dynamic wrinkles (crow''s feet, frown lines) AND perioral fine lines or lip area lines that remain at rest — patients seeking comprehensive upper and lower facial line improvement.","not_ideal_candidate":"Patients with only one zone of concern (upper face or perioral, not both), or patients hypersensitive to botulinum toxin or HA components.","concern_tags":["Dynamic Wrinkles","Perioral Lines","Crow''s Feet","Lip Lines","Fine Lines"],"why_together":"Botox and RHA Redensity treat complementary anatomical zones. Botox is most effective for upper-face dynamic lines; RHA Redensity''s flexible formulation is designed specifically for the dynamic perioral area that neurotoxin cannot treat effectively.","A_solves":"Botox relaxes the muscles causing dynamic lines in the upper face — crow''s feet, forehead, frown lines between the brows.","A_does_not_solve":"Botox cannot address the fine lines around the lips and perioral area; these require a filler that moves with facial expression rather than restricts it.","B_adds":"RHA Redensity uses a resilient HA formulation designed for the perioral zone''s high-mobility environment, softening the fine static lines around the lips that neurotoxin cannot treat.","clinical_rationale":"Neurotoxin relaxes dynamic muscles (upper face); RHA Redensity addresses perioral fine lines with flexible HA designed for dynamic areas around the mouth. The two treatments target complementary anatomical zones — Botox for forehead, crow''s feet, and frown lines, while RHA Redensity softens the fine static lines around the lips that neurotoxin cannot treat. Category-level evidence supports BoNT-A + HA filler combinations (DOI 10.1097/DSS.0000000000000754); no product-specific study exists for this pair. The perioral zone specificity of RHA Redensity is clinically sound and reflected in its FDA indication for dynamic perioral rhytids.","patient_education_summary":"Botox helps relax the muscles that cause expression lines — like frown lines and crow''s feet. But it can''t address the fine lines around your lips, which are caused by a combination of repeated movement and lost support in the skin. RHA Redensity is a flexible filler designed specifically for that area around the mouth — it moves with your expressions rather than fighting them. Many patients find that treating both the upper face lines and the perioral area creates a more complete, natural-looking result.","staff_close":"When a patient comes in concerned about fine lines both around the eyes and around the mouth, explain: ''Botox can help with the crow''s feet and forehead lines — those are caused by muscle movement. But the lines around your lips are different — they need a filler that can move with your expressions. RHA Redensity is designed for that dynamic area.''","staff_talking_points":"Some patients choose to address both in the same visit, while others prefer to start with one area and see how they feel. A zone-based explanation often resonates: upper face (movement) and lower face/perioral (volume + movement support). RHA Redensity''s perioral retreatment is every 6-12 months — shorter than most fillers — which is worth communicating upfront for scheduling expectations.","do_not_say":{"universal":["Unsupported clinical claims (e.g., ''clinically proven to reverse aging'')","Guarantees (e.g., ''I guarantee you''ll love the results'')","''You need this'' pressure (e.g., ''You really need both'')","Fear-based selling (e.g., ''Without this, your skin will only get worse'')","Competitor disparagement","''Liquid facelift'' overclaims","''No downtime'' when downtime exists","Permanent result claims","Off-label combination approval claims","''No risk'' statements","Price/value claims practices may not honor","Before/after exaggerations (e.g., ''20 years younger'')"],"pair_specific":["Do not suggest Botox around the mouth — perioral neurotoxin can impair speech, eating, and facial function and is not the clinical approach here.","Do not imply RHA Redensity adds ''volume'' to the lips in the way lip fillers do — it treats perioral rhytids (fine lines), not lip augmentation.","Do not overstate the perioral maintenance duration — RHA Redensity in the perioral area may require more frequent retreatment than other anatomical zones.","Do not claim product-specific evidence for this pair — the evidence base is category-level only."],"practice_specific":[]},"top_objections":[{"objection_type":"cost","patient_says":"I only wanted Botox today — can we talk about the perioral lines another time?","handling_language":"Of course. Botox and perioral filler are completely independent treatments — there''s no reason to do them at the same time. We can address the upper face today and revisit the perioral concern whenever you''re ready.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t suggest urgency. Don''t bundle a hard close."},{"objection_type":"do_I_need_both","patient_says":"Can''t Botox treat the lines around my mouth too?","handling_language":"The lines around the eyes and forehead are caused by muscle movement — that''s exactly what Botox addresses. But the fine lines around your mouth are in a different category. Some are caused by repeated movement, but they''re in a high-mobility zone where a flexible filler that moves with your expressions works better than reducing muscle movement. Trying to treat the perioral area with significant neurotoxin could actually affect normal lip function.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say Botox ''doesn''t work'' around the mouth. Clarify it''s about zone-appropriate treatment."},{"objection_type":"fear_of_looking_overdone","patient_says":"I don''t want my lips to look done.","handling_language":"RHA Redensity isn''t a lip augmentation — it''s specifically designed to treat the fine lines around the lips, not to add volume to the lips themselves. The goal is to soften those small lines while preserving natural lip shape. Your provider places very small amounts precisely at the line sites, not in the lip body.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t dismiss the concern. Clarify the distinction between perioral line treatment and lip augmentation."},{"objection_type":"downtime","patient_says":"The perioral area bruises easily. How long would I need?","handling_language":"That''s worth planning around. The perioral area does tend to bruise more easily for some patients, so if you have an event coming up, scheduling the Botox today and the perioral filler a few weeks after the event can be a practical approach. Your provider can advise based on your specific situation.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t dismiss the concern. Don''t say ''no bruising.''"},{"objection_type":"I_will_think_about_it","patient_says":"Let me think about the perioral filler — I''m not sure.","handling_language":"Completely fine. There''s no rush on this decision, and the two treatments are independent. We''ll do whatever you''re comfortable with today and keep the conversation open.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t push. Don''t reopen the sales conversation immediately."}],"sequencing_note":"Neurotoxin administered first in same-session protocols. If sequential: neurotoxin 2 weeks before perioral filler to assess muscle response in the upper face.","timing_note":"Same session or sequential visits. If sequential: 2-week interval recommended.","downtime_note":"Botox: full effect at 7-14 days, minimal visible downtime. RHA Redensity perioral: possible bruising and swelling; perioral area is particularly prone to bruising. Patients should be counseled to plan accordingly before events.","same_session_ok":true,"maintenance_story":"Botox every 3-4 months; RHA Redensity perioral every 6-12 months (perioral area typically requires more frequent retreatment than other zones due to high mobility). Patients should be advised that the perioral maintenance window is shorter than most HA fillers.","rebooking_trigger":"At your Botox follow-up, we can discuss the perioral lines — this is a natural time to evaluate how the upper face has responded and decide if you''d like to address the lower face.","next_visit_prompt":"If the perioral lines are still a concern after seeing your Botox results, we can discuss RHA Redensity at your next visit.","source_support_summary":"PubMed DOI 10.1097/DSS.0000000000000754: BoNT-A and HA fillers may be performed together in either sequence; combination superior to either alone. Category-level evidence extrapolated to this pair. FDA label — Botox Cosmetic: indicated for glabellar lines, lateral canthal lines, and forehead lines in adults. FDA label — RHA Redensity: indicated for injection into the perioral area (superficial to mid dermis) for correction of dynamic perioral rhytids in adults over 22. Accepted clinical practice: zone-based complementarity (upper-face neurotoxin + perioral filler) is standard in comprehensive facial rejuvenation protocols.","evidence_level":"moderate","review_status":"draft","audience":["agent","staff"],"patient_safe":false,"last_reviewed":null,"reviewed_by":null}'::jsonb,
    status  = 'draft'
WHERE fuel_type = 'pairing_fuel'
  AND content->>'pair_key' = 'botox_cosmetic__rha_redensity';

-- Pair 5: Smooth & Glow (botox_cosmetic__skinvive_by_juvederm)
-- Review status: PENDING
-- Tier: combination | Evidence: weak
UPDATE agent_fuel_documents
SET
    content = '{"fuel_type":"combination","template_version":"1.0","pair_key":"botox_cosmetic__skinvive_by_juvederm","patient_facing_name":"Smooth & Glow","one_line_positioning":"Botox reduces expression lines while SKINVIVE improves the overall cheek skin smoothness that neurotoxin cannot address.","package_goal":"Reduce expression lines and improve cheek skin smoothness and quality","ideal_candidate":"Adult patients presenting with dynamic expression lines AND concerns about overall skin quality, dullness, or lack of skin smoothness who want to address both line reduction and skin quality in a combined plan.","not_ideal_candidate":"Patients seeking traditional volume augmentation (SKINVIVE does not add structural volume), or patients with hypersensitivity to botulinum toxin or HA components.","concern_tags":["Dynamic Wrinkles","Skin Quality","Skin Texture","Skin Hydration","Dullness"],"why_together":"Botox and SKINVIVE address completely different aspects of skin appearance. Botox reduces movement-caused lines through muscle relaxation; SKINVIVE improves cheek skin smoothness through intradermal microdroplet HA hydration. They do not overlap in mechanism or target tissue.","A_solves":"Botox relaxes the muscles causing dynamic expression lines (frown lines, crow''s feet, forehead) — lines that appear when you move your face.","A_does_not_solve":"Botox cannot improve overall skin texture, hydration, or skin quality — it does not act on the skin itself, only on the underlying muscle.","B_adds":"SKINVIVE improves cheek skin smoothness through microdroplet intradermal HA, addressing overall skin quality that Botox cannot improve. It is not a volume filler — it does not add structural volume.","clinical_rationale":"Neurotoxin relaxes dynamic muscles; SKINVIVE improves skin quality via microdroplet HA injection. These target fundamentally different aspects of facial aging — Botox addresses movement-caused lines while SKINVIVE addresses skin texture, hydration, and overall cheek skin smoothness that neurotoxin cannot improve. The combination provides both line reduction and skin quality enhancement, addressing two of the most common patient concerns. Note: SKINVIVE is a microdroplet skin quality product (not a traditional volumizing filler), so BoNT-A + filler combination studies do not directly apply. The evidence base is expert consensus from accepted clinical practice; no published controlled trial for this specific pairing exists.","patient_education_summary":"Botox helps relax the muscles that cause expression lines — like frown lines and crow''s feet. But even when those lines are smoothed, your skin might still look dull or feel rough. SKINVIVE is different from traditional fillers — it doesn''t add volume. Instead, it uses tiny microdroplets of hyaluronic acid to hydrate the skin from within, improving cheek skin smoothness that lasts about six months. One addresses the lines, the other improves the skin itself. Many patients find the combination gives them a fresher, more rested look overall.","staff_close":"When a patient is focused on looking refreshed: ''Botox can help with the expression lines — frown lines, crow''s feet, forehead. But some patients tell us even after Botox, their skin still doesn''t look as vibrant as they''d like. SKINVIVE isn''t a filler in the traditional sense — it doesn''t add volume or fill wrinkles. It hydrates the skin from within using microdroplets, improving cheek skin smoothness.''","staff_talking_points":"The key distinction to communicate: SKINVIVE and Botox solve completely different problems — lines vs. skin quality. SKINVIVE is not a traditional filler, so patients who associate ''filler'' with lip augmentation or volumizing may need clarification. Some patients choose to address both, while others prefer to start with one and add later. SKINVIVE''s ~6-month maintenance window aligns reasonably with 2 Botox cycles (3-4 months each), which helps with scheduling discussions.","do_not_say":{"universal":["Unsupported clinical claims (e.g., ''clinically proven to reverse aging'')","Guarantees (e.g., ''I guarantee you''ll love the results'')","''You need this'' pressure (e.g., ''You really need both'')","Fear-based selling (e.g., ''Without this, your skin will only get worse'')","Competitor disparagement","''Liquid facelift'' overclaims","''No downtime'' when downtime exists","Permanent result claims","Off-label combination approval claims","''No risk'' statements","Price/value claims practices may not honor","Before/after exaggerations (e.g., ''20 years younger'')"],"pair_specific":["Do not describe SKINVIVE as a filler that ''adds volume'' — it is an intradermal microdroplet HA product for skin quality improvement, not volumization.","Do not overstate the evidence for this combination — the evidence base is expert consensus only; no published controlled trial exists for BoNT-A + microdroplet HA.","Do not describe SKINVIVE''s FDA indication beyond cheek skin smoothness — the indication is specific to cheek skin smoothness in adults over 21, not broad skin quality or full-face application.","Do not guarantee specific ''glow'' outcomes — the FDA glow scale was used in the SKINVIVE trial, but outcome language should remain realistic."],"practice_specific":[]},"top_objections":[{"objection_type":"cost","patient_says":"Do I need to do SKINVIVE and Botox at the same time?","handling_language":"Not at all. These treat completely different things — you can do either one independently, or start with one and add the other later. Many patients start with Botox and then consider SKINVIVE at a future visit once they''ve seen their Botox results.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t create urgency. Don''t imply Botox is incomplete without SKINVIVE."},{"objection_type":"do_I_need_both","patient_says":"What does SKINVIVE do that Botox doesn''t?","handling_language":"They work on completely different things. Botox relaxes the muscles that cause expression lines. SKINVIVE doesn''t touch the muscles at all — it''s placed in the skin itself as microdroplets that improve cheek skin smoothness and hydration from within. If your concern is the skin quality between the wrinkles — the texture, the dullness — that''s what SKINVIVE addresses. Botox alone won''t improve skin quality.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say ''Botox isn''t enough.'' Just explain what each does."},{"objection_type":"filler_concern","patient_says":"Is SKINVIVE a filler? I don''t want to look puffy.","handling_language":"SKINVIVE is different from traditional fillers. It doesn''t add visible volume the way cheek or lip fillers do. It uses very small microdroplets of hyaluronic acid placed just under the skin''s surface — the change is in skin quality (smoothness and hydration), not in facial structure or shape. There''s no puffiness or added volume.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t dismiss the ''filler'' concern without addressing it clearly. Be specific about what SKINVIVE does and doesn''t do."},{"objection_type":"downtime","patient_says":"I''m worried about downtime from both procedures at once.","handling_language":"Both treatments have minimal downtime — you may have some temporary redness or minor swelling at injection sites, but most patients go back to normal activities the same day. Combining them in one visit does mean more injection sites, so if you''d prefer to minimize any potential temporary marks, spacing them out is always an option.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say ''no downtime.'' There is potential for minor redness and swelling."},{"objection_type":"I_will_think_about_it","patient_says":"I hadn''t considered SKINVIVE before. Let me think about it.","handling_language":"Of course. There''s no reason to decide today. We can proceed with Botox and keep the SKINVIVE conversation for a future visit. Happy to answer any questions you have when you''re ready.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t apply pressure. Don''t reopen the conversation multiple times in one visit."}],"sequencing_note":"Neurotoxin administered first, SKINVIVE microdroplets second. SKINVIVE is typically a finishing step as it addresses the skin surface layer.","timing_note":"Same session or sequential visits. If sequential: neurotoxin 2 weeks before SKINVIVE. SKINVIVE microdroplets are placed intradermally and do not interact with neurotoxin placement.","downtime_note":"Minimal for both. Temporary redness or minor swelling at injection sites possible. SKINVIVE: microdroplet placement is intradermal with minimal visible downtime. Botox: full effect at 7-14 days.","same_session_ok":true,"maintenance_story":"Botox every 3-4 months; SKINVIVE every 6-9 months. SKINVIVE''s maintenance schedule aligns with approximately 2 Botox cycles, meaning patients may be able to co-schedule SKINVIVE renewals with one of their semi-annual Botox visits.","rebooking_trigger":"At your Botox 2-week follow-up, if you''d like to discuss the skin quality piece, that''s a natural time to revisit the SKINVIVE conversation.","next_visit_prompt":"If you''d like to address skin quality or cheek skin smoothness in addition to the expression lines, SKINVIVE is worth discussing at your next visit.","source_support_summary":"FDA label — Botox Cosmetic: indicated for glabellar lines, lateral canthal lines, and forehead lines in adults. FDA label — SKINVIVE by Juvederm: indicated for improvement of cheek skin smoothness in adults over 21. Accepted clinical practice: BoNT-A and intradermal HA microdroplet products target different tissue layers and mechanisms (neuromodulation vs intradermal hydration), supporting clinical rationale for combination use. No published controlled trial for BoNT-A + microdroplet HA combination. No published contraindication to concurrent administration.","evidence_level":"weak","review_status":"draft","audience":["agent","staff"],"patient_safe":false,"last_reviewed":null,"reviewed_by":null}'::jsonb,
    status  = 'draft'
WHERE fuel_type = 'pairing_fuel'
  AND content->>'pair_key' = 'botox_cosmetic__skinvive_by_juvederm';

