SET
    content = '{"fuel_type":"combination","template_version":"1.0","pair_key":"botox_cosmetic__sculptra_aesthetic","patient_facing_name":"Smooth & Rebuild","one_line_positioning":"Botox relaxes expression lines immediately while Sculptra supports collagen production over months — addressing two different aspects of aging on different timelines.","package_goal":"Reduce dynamic wrinkles and support long-term collagen structure","ideal_candidate":"Adult patients concerned about both current dynamic expression lines and progressive volume/collagen loss who want both immediate correction and a gradual structural foundation. Patients planning long-term facial aging management.","not_ideal_candidate":"Patients seeking only immediate visible results, patients hypersensitive to botulinum toxin or poly-L-lactic acid, patients who cannot commit to the multi-session Sculptra series (2-3 treatments), or pregnant/nursing patients.","concern_tags":["Dynamic Wrinkles","Collagen Loss","Volume Loss","Skin Laxity","Facial Aging"],"why_together":"Botox and Sculptra address two fundamentally different aspects of aging through orthogonal mechanisms. Botox delivers immediate, reversible neuromodulation; Sculptra delivers gradual, durable collagen stimulation. Neither can do what the other does.","A_solves":"Botox relaxes the muscles that create dynamic expression lines (crow''s feet, frown lines, forehead) — providing immediate, visible wrinkle reduction.","A_does_not_solve":"Botox cannot reverse skin laxity, support collagen production, or address the gradual structural volume loss that comes from collagen breakdown over time.","B_adds":"Sculptra stimulates the body''s own collagen production over a series of treatments, gradually restoring structural support and volume that neurotoxin cannot provide.","clinical_rationale":"Neurotoxin relaxes dynamic muscles (immediate effect); Sculptra stimulates collagen production (gradual effect over months). These address two fundamentally different aspects of aging — movement-caused lines and collagen/volume loss — through completely different mechanisms at different tissue depths and timelines. The combination provides both immediate dynamic wrinkle reduction and long-term structural improvement. Note: No published controlled trial data exists for this specific combination. The FDA Sculptra label states that safety and effectiveness in combination with other products have not been evaluated in controlled clinical trials. Expert consensus supports this combination in clinical practice.","patient_education_summary":"Botox helps with lines from muscle movement, but over time you also lose the underlying volume and structure. Sculptra works over months to support collagen production. They address different parts of the aging process — Botox handles the lines caused by expressions, while Sculptra gradually supports the structure underneath. Your provider may suggest using both, depending on your individual situation. This combination is used in clinical practice, but it has not been evaluated in controlled clinical trials, so your provider can discuss whether it makes sense for you.","staff_close":"When a patient is concerned about both expression lines and overall facial volume loss, explain: ''There are really two different things happening. The lines around your eyes and forehead are from muscle movement — that''s what Botox addresses. But the overall loss of fullness and structure is from collagen breakdown over time. Sculptra works gradually to support collagen production.'' Frame it as an option the provider may recommend based on the patient''s individual needs, not as a standard protocol.","staff_talking_points":"This combination is used in clinical practice but has not been evaluated in controlled trials. Staff should not present it as a standard or recommended protocol — it is a provider-recommended option. Sculptra requires a series of 2-3 sessions 4-6 weeks apart before patients see results, which is worth communicating upfront. Some providers prefer to establish Sculptra collagen stimulation first, then layer Botox for dynamic lines. The timeline difference (Botox: days; Sculptra: months) should be explained so patients have realistic expectations.","do_not_say":{"universal":["Unsupported clinical claims (e.g., ''clinically proven to reverse aging'')","Guarantees (e.g., ''I guarantee you''ll love the results'')","''You need this'' pressure (e.g., ''You really need both'')","Fear-based selling (e.g., ''Without this, your skin will only get worse'')","Competitor disparagement","''Liquid facelift'' overclaims","''No downtime'' when downtime exists","Permanent result claims","Off-label combination approval claims","''No risk'' statements","Price/value claims practices may not honor","Before/after exaggerations (e.g., ''20 years younger'')"],"pair_specific":["Do not describe Sculptra results as ''immediate'' — Sculptra works gradually over months and requires multiple sessions before visible results appear.","Do not state the combination is FDA approved as a package — the FDA Sculptra label explicitly notes that safety and effectiveness in combination with other products have not been evaluated in controlled clinical trials.","Do not describe Sculptra as a ''filler'' — it is a biostimulator that stimulates the body''s collagen production; it does not add a foreign material that fills space.","Do not guarantee the number of sessions needed — Sculptra treatment protocols are individualized by provider."],"practice_specific":[]},"top_objections":[{"objection_type":"cost","patient_says":"Sculptra is expensive and takes multiple sessions. Is it really worth adding to Botox?","handling_language":"That''s a fair question. Sculptra and Botox are addressing different things — Botox handles the expression lines, Sculptra works on the underlying structure over time. Whether adding Sculptra makes sense depends on your individual goals and what your provider recommends for your specific situation. There''s no requirement to do both.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say ''it''s worth it'' without understanding the patient''s specific concerns and goals. Don''t push the combination if the patient''s goals are adequately served by Botox alone."},{"objection_type":"do_I_need_both","patient_says":"I thought Botox alone would be enough. Why would I need Sculptra too?","handling_language":"Botox works really well for expression lines — the lines that appear when your face moves. But Sculptra addresses something different: the gradual loss of collagen and volume over time. That''s not something Botox can address. Whether you want to work on both at once, or start with Botox and revisit the structural piece later, is your decision and your provider can guide you.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t imply Botox is inadequate. The patient may be right that Botox is all they need right now."},{"objection_type":"timeline","patient_says":"I want to see results soon. How long does Sculptra take?","handling_language":"Sculptra works gradually over months — that''s actually how it works. It supports your body''s collagen production, so results build over time rather than appearing immediately. Most patients see changes over 2-4 months and require 2-3 treatment sessions. Botox, on the other hand, shows results within days. If you want something you can see quickly, Botox provides that while Sculptra works in the background.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say Sculptra works ''right away'' or overpromise on timeline. Set realistic expectations."},{"objection_type":"safety_concern","patient_says":"Is it safe to do both at the same time?","handling_language":"This combination is used in clinical practice by many providers. The FDA Sculptra label notes that combination use with other products hasn''t been formally studied in controlled trials, which is why it''s something your provider assesses for your individual situation rather than a standard protocol. Your provider can explain whether this makes sense for you.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t say ''completely safe'' without acknowledging the FDA label limitation. Don''t dismiss the safety question."},{"objection_type":"I_will_think_about_it","patient_says":"Can I just do Botox today and think about Sculptra later?","handling_language":"Absolutely. These are independent decisions. Many patients start with Botox and revisit the structural conversation over time as they see how their skin changes. There''s no urgency on the Sculptra decision.","do_not_say_in_response":"Don''t create urgency. Don''t say Sculptra needs to be started now."}],"sequencing_note":"Same session or staggered. If same session, no known interaction risk given different tissue depths. Some providers prefer to establish Sculptra series first, then layer neurotoxin. If sequential: neurotoxin can be done at any point in the Sculptra series.","timing_note":"Long-term plan: Botox every 3-4 months; Sculptra series of 2-3 sessions 4-6 weeks apart, then annual maintenance.","downtime_note":"Botox: minimal, full effect at 7-14 days. Sculptra: injection site swelling and bruising possible; Sculptra massage protocol (5-5-5) required post-treatment. Sculptra results appear gradually over months — not an immediate result.","same_session_ok":"conditional — same session performed in clinical practice; FDA Sculptra label notes combination use not evaluated in controlled clinical trials; provider should discuss caveat with patient","maintenance_story":"Botox every 3-4 months; Sculptra series of 2-3 sessions 4-6 weeks apart for initial treatment, then annual maintenance session. Long-term plan: patients coordinate Sculptra annual touch-ups with their regular Botox schedule. The two-treatment plan is a multi-year commitment.","rebooking_trigger":"At your Botox follow-up, if you''re interested in discussing the structural piece, we can assess your collagen support needs at that visit.","next_visit_prompt":"If long-term structural support is a goal, we can discuss Sculptra when you''re ready — at your Botox follow-up or any time.","source_support_summary":"FDA Sculptra Aesthetic labeling: indicated for correction of shallow to deep nasolabial fold contour deficiencies and other facial wrinkles. ''The safety and effectiveness of SCULPTRA Aesthetic used in combination with other products and procedures have not been evaluated in controlled clinical trials.'' FDA label — Botox Cosmetic: indicated for glabellar lines, lateral canthal lines, and forehead lines in adults. Expert consensus: expert consensus supports this combination in clinical practice based on orthogonal mechanisms (neuromodulation vs PLLA biostimulation at different tissue depths).","evidence_level":"weak","review_status":"draft","audience":["agent","staff"],"patient_safe":false,"last_reviewed":null,"reviewed_by":null}'::jsonb,
    status  = 'draft'
